[0.000, "o", "\u001b[66;2H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fL\u001b[m\u000f Refresh\u001b[18G\u001b[23X\u001b[66;41H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^F\u001b[m\u000f Where Is      \u001b[66;69H            \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-B\u001b[m\u000f Previous    \u001b[103G        \u001b[66;120H \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^P\u001b[m\u000f Prev Line\u001b[28X\u001b[66;161H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^Y\u001b[m\u000f Prev Page    \u001b[66;188H             \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-\\\u001b[m\u000f First Line\u001b[K\u001b[67;4HClose\u001b[67;18H\u001b[23X\u001b[67;41H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^B\u001b[m\u000f Where Was       \u001b[67;69H            \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-F\u001b[m\u000f Next\u001b[22X\u001b[67;120H \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^N\u001b[m\u000f Next Line\u001b[28X\u001b[67;161H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^V\u001b[m\u000f Next Page       \u001b[67;188H"]
[0.000, "o", "             \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-/\u001b[m\u000f Last Line\u001b[K\u001b[1;3H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f            \u001b[1;111H Main nano help text   \u001b[1;231H        \u001b[m\u000f"]
[0.001, "o", "\r\u001b[2d\u001b[K\u001b[3d The nano editor is designed to emulate the functionality and ease-of-use\r\u001b[4d of the UW Pico text editor.  There are four main sections of the editor.\r\u001b[5d The top line shows the program version, the current filename being\r\u001b[6d edited, and whether or not the file has been modified.  Next is the main\r\u001b[7d editor window showing the file being edited.  The status line is the\r\u001b[8d third line from the bottom and shows important messages.  The bottom two\r\u001b[9d lines show the most commonly used shortcuts in the editor.\r\u001b[10d\u001b[K\u001b[11d Shortcuts are written as follows: Control-key sequences are notated with\r\u001b[12d a '^' and can be entered either by using the Ctrl key or pressing the Esc\r\u001b[13d key twice.  Meta-key sequences are notated with 'M-' and can be entered\r\u001b[14d using either the Alt, Cmd, or Esc key, depending on your keyboard setup.\r\u001b[15d Also, pressing Esc twice and then typing a three-digit decimal number\r\u001b[16d from 000 to 255 will enter the character with the corresponding value.\r\u001b[17d The following keystrokes are available in the main editor window.\r\u001b[18d Alternative keys are shown in parentheses:\r\u001b[19d\u001b[K\u001b[20d^G     (F1)      Display this help text\r\u001b[21d^X     (F2)      Close the current buffer / Exit from nano\r\u001b[22d^O     (F3)\u001b[18GWrite the current buffer (or the marked region) to disk\r\u001b[23d^R     (Ins)     Insert another file into current buffer (or into new buffer)\r\u001b[24d\u001b[K\u001b[25d"]
[0.001, "o", "^F     (^W)      Search forward for a string or a regular expression\r\u001b[26d^\\     (M-R)     Replace a string or a regular expression\r\u001b[27d^K     (F9)\u001b[18GCut current line (or marked region) and store it in cutbuffer\r\u001b[28d^U     (F10)     Paste the contents of cutbuffer at current cursor position\r\u001b[29d\u001b[K\u001b[30d^T\u001b[15X\u001b[30;18HExecute a function or an external command\r\u001b[31d^J     (F4)\u001b[18GJustify the current paragraph\r\u001b[32d\u001b[K\u001b[33d^C     (F11)     Display the position of the cursor\r\u001b[34d^/     (M-G)     Go to line and column number\r\u001b[35d\u001b[K\u001b[36dM-U\u001b[14X\u001b[36;18HUndo the last operation\u001b[K\r\u001b[37dM-E\u001b[14X\u001b[37;18HRedo the last undone operation\u001b[K\r\u001b[38d\u001b[K\u001b[39dM-A    (^6)      Mark text starting from the cursor position\u001b[K\r\u001b[40dM-6    (M-^)     Copy current line (or marked region) and store it in cutbuffer\r\u001b[41d\u001b[K\u001b[42dM-]\u001b[14X\u001b[42;18HGo to the matching bracket\u001b[K\r\u001b[43d\u001b[K\u001b[44d^B     (^Q)      Search backward for a string or a regular expression\u001b[K\r\u001b[45dM-B    (M-Q)     Search next occurrence backward\r\u001b[46d"]
[0.000, "o", "M-F    (M-W)     Search next occurrence forward\r\u001b[47d\u001b[K\u001b[48d◂\u001b[16X\u001b[48;18HGo back one character\r\u001b[49d"]
[0.000, "o", "▸\u001b[49;18HGo forward one character\r\u001b[50d^◂     (M-Space) Go back one word\u001b[K\r\u001b[51d"]
[0.000, "o", "^▸     (^Space)  Go forward one word\r\u001b[52d^A     (Home)    Go to beginning of current line\u001b[K\r\u001b[53d^E     (End)     Go to end of current line\r\u001b[54dM-<\u001b[14X\u001b[54;18HScroll the viewport a tabsize to the left\r\u001b[55dM->\u001b[14X\u001b[55;18HScroll the viewport a tabsize to the right\r\u001b[57d^P     (▴)       Go to previous line\u001b[K\r\u001b[58d^N     (▾)       Go to next line\u001b[K\r\u001b[59dM-▴    (M--)     Scroll up one line without moving the cursor textually\u001b[K\r\u001b[60dM-▾    (M-+)     Scroll down one line without moving the cursor textually\u001b[K\r\u001b[61d\u001b[K\u001b[62d^▴     (M-7)     Go to previous block of text\r\u001b[63d^▾     (M-8)     Go to next block of text\u001b[K\r\u001b[64dM-(    (M-9)     Go to beginning of paragraph; then of previous paragraph\r\u001b[2d"]
[5.762, "o", "\u001b[66;2H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fG\u001b[m\u000f Help   \u001b[18G\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^O\u001b[m\u000f Write Out     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^F\u001b[m\u000f Where Is      \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^K\u001b[m\u000f Cut\u001b[66;69H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^T\u001b[m\u000f Execute       \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^C\u001b[m\u000f Location\u001b[103G\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-U\u001b[m\u000f Undo\u001b[66;120H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-A\u001b[m\u000f Set Mark     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-]\u001b[m\u000f To Bracket   \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-B\u001b[m\u000f Previous     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f◂\u001b[m\u000f Back\u001b[66;188H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^◂\u001b[m\u000f Prev Word     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^A\u001b[m\u000f Home   \u001b[222G\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-<\u001b[m\u000f Scroll Left\u001b[67;4HExit \u001b[67;18H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^R\u001b[m\u000f Read File     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^\\\u001b[m\u000f Replace       \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^U\u001b[m\u000f Paste\u001b[67;69H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^J\u001b[m\u000f Justify       \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^/\u001b[m\u000f Go To Line    \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-E\u001b[m\u000f Redo\u001b[67;120H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-6\u001b[m\u000f Copy         \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^B\u001b[m\u000f Where Was     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM-F\u001b[m\u000f Next         \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f▸\u001b[m\u000f Forward\u001b[67;188H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^▸\u001b[m\u000f Next Word     \u001b[0;10;7m\u000f^E\u001b[m\u000f End   \u001b[67;222H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fM->\u001b[m\u000f Scroll Right\u001b[1;3H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000fGNU nano 9.0\u001b[1;111H/etc/php-legacy/php.ini\u001b[1;231HModified\u001b[m\u000f"]
[0.001, "o", "\r\u001b[2dpgsql.max_links = -1\r\u001b[3d\u001b[K\u001b[4d; Ignore PostgreSQL backends Notice message or not.\u001b[K\r\u001b[5d; Notice message logging require a little overheads.\u001b[K\r\u001b[6d; https://php.net/pgsql.ignore-notice\u001b[K\r\u001b[7dpgsql.ignore_notice = 0\u001b[K\r\u001b[8d\u001b[K\u001b[9d; Log PostgreSQL backends Notice message or not.\u001b[K\r\u001b[10d; Unless pgsql.ignore_notice=0, module cannot log notice message.\r\u001b[11d; https://php.net/pgsql.log-notice\u001b[K\r\u001b[12dpgsql.log_notice = 0\u001b[K\r\u001b[13d\u001b[K\u001b[14d[bcmath]\u001b[K\r\u001b[15d; Number of decimal digits for all bcmath functions.\u001b[K\r\u001b[16d; https://php.net/bcmath.scale\u001b[K\r\u001b[17dbcmath.scale = 0\u001b[K\r\u001b[18d\u001b[K\u001b[19d[browscap]\r\u001b[20d; https://php.net/browscap\u001b[K\r\u001b[21d;browscap = extra/browscap.ini\u001b[K\r\u001b[22d\u001b[K\u001b[23d"]
[0.000, "o", "[Session]\u001b[K\r\u001b[24d; Handler used to store/retrieve data.\r\u001b[25d; https://php.net/session.save-handler\u001b[K\r\u001b[26dsession.save_handler = files\u001b[K\r\u001b[27d\u001b[K\u001b[28d"]
[0.001, "o", "; Argument passed to save_handler.  In the case of files, this is the path\u001b[K\r\u001b[29d; where data files are stored. Note: Windows users have to change this\r\u001b[30d; variable in order to use PHP's session functions.\u001b[K\r\u001b[31d;\u001b[K\u001b[32d\b; The path can be defined as:\r\u001b[33d;\u001b[K\u001b[34d\b;     session.save_path = \"N;/path\"\u001b[K\r\u001b[35d;\u001b[36d\b; where N is an integer.  Instead of storing all the session files in\r\u001b[37d"]
[0.000, "o", "; /path, what this will do is use subdirectories N-levels deep, and\r\u001b[38d; store the session data in those directories.  This is useful if\r\u001b[39d; your OS has problems with many files in one directory, and is\r\u001b[40d; a more efficient layout for servers that handle many sessions.\u001b[K\r\u001b[41d;\u001b[42d\b; NOTE 1: PHP will not create this directory structure automatically.\r\u001b[43d;\u001b[43;11HYou can use the script in the ext/session dir for that purpose.\r\u001b[44d; NOTE 2: See the section on garbage collection below if you choose to\r\u001b[45d;         use subdirectories for session storage\r\u001b[46d;\u001b[K\u001b[47d\b; The file storage module creates files using mode 600 by default.\r\u001b[48d; You can change that by using\u001b[K\r\u001b[49d;\u001b[K\u001b[50d\b;     session.save_path = \"N;MODE;/path\"\r\u001b[51d"]
[0.000, "o", ";\u001b[K\u001b[52d\b; where MODE is the octal representation of the mode. Note that this\r\u001b[53d; does not overwrite the process's umask.\u001b[K\r\u001b[54d; https://php.net/session.save-path\u001b[K\r\u001b[55d;session.save_path = \"/tmp\"\u001b[K\r\u001b[57d; Whether to use strict session mode.\r\u001b[58d"]
[0.000, "o", "; Strict session mode does not accept an uninitialized session ID, and\r\u001b[59d; regenerates the session ID if the browser sends an uninitialized session ID.\r\u001b[60d"]
[0.000, "o", "; Strict mode protects applications from session fixation via a session adoption\r\u001b[61d; vulnerability. It is disabled by default for maximum compatibility, but\r\u001b[62d; enabling it is encouraged.\u001b[K\r\u001b[63d; https://wiki.php.net/rfc/strict_sessions\r\u001b[64dsession.use_strict_mode = 0\u001b[K\r\u001b[?25h\u001b[?0c"]
