[0.001, "o", "\r\u001b[2d; security context that the request runs under.  mod_fastcgi under Apache\u001b[3;3Hdoes not currently support this feature (03/17/2002)\u001b[K\r\u001b[4d; Set to 1 if running under IIS.  Default is zero.\r\u001b[5d; https://php.net/fastcgi.impersonate\r\u001b[6d;fastcgi.impersonate = 1\u001b[K\r\u001b[7d\u001b[K\u001b[8;4Hisable logging through FastCGI connection. PHP's default behavior is to enable\r\u001b[9d; this feature.\u001b[K\r\u001b[10d;fastcgi.logging = 0\r\u001b[11d\u001b[K\u001b[12d; cgi.rfc2616_headers configuration option tells PHP what type of headers to\r\u001b[13d; use when sending HTTP response code. If set to 0, PHP sends Status: header that\r\u001b[14d; is supported by Apache. When this option is set to 1, PHP will send\r\u001b[15d; RFC2616 compliant header.\u001b[K\u001b[16;3HDefault is zero.\u001b[K\r\u001b[17d;"]
[0.000, "o", " https://php.net/cgi.rfc2616-headers\r\u001b[18d;cgi.rfc2616_headers = 0\r\u001b[19d\u001b[K\u001b[20d; cgi.check_shebang_line controls whether CGI PHP checks for line starting with #!\u001b[21;3H(shebang) at the top of the running script. This line might be needed if the\u001b[22;3Hscript support running both as stand-alone script and via PHP CGI<. PHP in CGI\u001b[23;3H"]
